import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the dataset that i downloaded from kaggle
data = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\lenovo\\Desktop\\salaries_cyber.csv")

# fig1:Represent the distribution of Salary
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))#size of fig
sns.histplot(data['salary'], bins=30, kde=True, color='purple')#histogram of salary and bins i explain it docs
plt.xlabel('Salary', fontsize=8)  
plt.ylabel('Density', fontsize=8)  
plt.title('Distribution of Salary', fontsize=10)  
plt.show()

# fig2: Filtered distribution of Salary
salary_threshold = data['salary'].quantile(0.99)
#calculates the 99th percentile of the 'salary' column in the dataset
#filter out extreme values or outliers from the salary data.
filtered_data = data[data['salary'] <= salary_threshold]
#line creates a new DataFrame called filtered_data by filtering the original dataset (data) based on the calculated salary_threshold.
#It selects only those rows from the original dataset where the 'salary' column value is less than or equal to the salary_threshold.
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

sns.histplot(filtered_data['salary'], bins=30, kde=True, color='yellow')
plt.xlabel('Salary', fontsize=8)  
plt.ylabel('Density', fontsize=8)  
plt.title('Filtered Distribution of Salary', fontsize=10)  
plt.show()


#fig3: Explore Categorical Variables
categorical_vars = ['experience_level', 'employment_type', 'job_title', 'company_size']
for var in categorical_vars:
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.countplot(data=data, x=var, palette='viridis', hue=var, legend=False)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=6) 
    plt.xlabel(var, fontsize=6)  
    plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=6)  
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Plot 4: Analyze Numerical Variables
numerical_vars = ['work_year', 'remote_ratio', 'salary_in_usd']
for var in numerical_vars:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.histplot(data=data[var], bins=30, kde=True, color='skyblue')
    plt.xlabel(var, fontsize=8)  
    plt.ylabel('Density', fontsize=8)  
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

#fig5: Investigate Relationships
for var in ['experience_level', 'employment_type', 'job_title']:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=var, y='salary_in_usd')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=6)  
    plt.xlabel(var, fontsize=6)  
    plt.ylabel('Salary (USD)', fontsize=8)  
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Plot 6: Correlation Analysis
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(data[numerical_vars].corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f")
plt.title('Correlation Matrix', fontsize=10)  
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Plot 7: Geographical Analysis
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.barplot(data=data, x='employee_residence', y='salary_in_usd', hue='employee_residence', legend=False, palette='plasma')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=6)  
plt.xlabel('Employee Residence', fontsize=6)  
plt.ylabel('Average Salary (USD)', fontsize=8)
plt.title('Average Salary by Employee Residence', fontsize=10)

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
sns.barplot(data=data, x='company_location', y='salary_in_usd', hue='company_location', legend=False, palette='plasma')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=6)  
plt.xlabel('Company Location', fontsize=6)  
plt.ylabel('Average Salary (USD)', fontsize=8)
plt.title('Average Salary by Company Location', fontsize=10)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
